column49: The teacher does a good job researching best practices and planning and implementing effective instruction in the subject area observed.
column53: The teacher manages instructional time well, but is having difficulty implementing successful behavior management techniques since a new student was recently added to her class. Her new student is causing significant disruptions throughout the day and the teacher is working on a behavior plan for that student.
column57: The teacher uses some assessment data to inform instruction and typically asks lower level questions that do not fully challenge students.
column59: The teacher is very reflective on her teaching, but continues to learn how to improve instruction as she becomes more familiar with best practices and curriculum in each subject area.

column49: The lesson plan provided with the is lesson included all aspect that is reqyired in a lesson plan.  The lesson plan was very specific with a beginning, middle and closing for the lesson.  It included the individual and group objectives for the class, procedures and materials needed.  This lesson plan can be followed by any teacher who has to substitute in the classroom.
column53: Alice provides a motivating, nurturing environment for all the students in class.  She has set up systems for student self check, student to student socialization and mutual respect with the students in her class.  She speaks to them in a kind yet forceful way and as a result has little behavioral challenges during her lesson.
column57: Though a specific assessment was not evident in her video it is written into her lesson plan as part ofher procedures.
column59: Alice continues to reflect on her professional growth.  She has taken my suggestions and has incorporated them into her already developed systems in her classroom.  Her increase in all aspects of her pedagogy is evident in the reductions of behavioral challenges in her classroom.

column49: The lesson plan submitted is a framework for the unit being taught. It includes objectives, gosals for small group guided practices and assessments.  It does not include individual goals and objectives for your students or group set up by names.  Your lesson plan also needs to include connection to standards and individual IEP goals.  It should also be connected to your oeriodic assessments such as SANDI or ABLLS.
column53: The behavioral challenges were dealt with in a non distrubtive way.  There were only 1 time where the class needed to be redirected.  At that time miguel started counting from 1-5 which was a signal to the students to face him and stop talking.  There was much improvement in his reaction to students talking during his lesson.  As discussed before, talking is a form of socialization so before you stop it see what the conversation are about.
column57: The instructional strategies used for this group  lesson included an auditory video that enriched and reinforced the sequence of the month of the year.  The activity that followed was presented in a motivating approach by having each student answer a question and place the answer of the board.  The final part of the lesson was to unsequence the months and have students recognize the corresponding number.  This part was introduced but video did not show the completion.
column59: Miguel continues to reflect on his overall professional growth and has been able to successfully put my suggestions into his instructional practices.  The improvement in his classroom management and questioning techniques show a growth in his pedagogy.

column49: Nate began his lesson with a review of what are the guidelines in writing when you use a story starter to create a story of fact.  He reviewed to start you need to restate the question, give examples of why you feel this way and end with a conclusion.  He gave them an example of answering the question and then had them work indepemdently to answer question.  During the independent writing he walked around and conference with each student.
column53: Nate's classroom is consistantly changing students which changes the climate of his classroom.  Inspite of this he has managed to create an environment where student listen to his direction and adhere to the rules of his classroom and school.
column57: During the independent writing he managed to conference with each student to check their work and make corrections when necessary.  I did not observe any formal data collection during this time.
column59: Nate continues to show a positive attitude throughout his lesson. He continues to reflect on his professional growth and adjusts his pedogogy when new students enter his class. He has taken my suggestions and have incorporated them into his practice.  He is using positive reinforcement to refocus student into making better choices both academically and behaviorally.

column57: Teacher is very effective in presenting higher level critical thinking questions for the students throughout the lesson which served to reinforce and challenge their thinking and understanding of the lesson objectives and key concepts. column59: Teacher is strong in her ability to reflect on her teaching practice and to make practical and meaningful suggestions to improve her lesson planning and delivery for the benefit of the students. column49: This was a well planned and very challenging lesson in physics for the ICT class.  The instructional outcomes and key concepts were clearly presented by the teacher.  The activities and tasks of the lesson were well planned, well aligned with the lesson objectives and meaningful for the students.  The tasks were engaging, challenging and motivating for the students.  Inclusion of much more specific differentiation for LD students in the lesson plan and, most importantly, during the lesson is very strongly recommended and encouraged.
column53: Students were appropriately engaged in the lesson and student behavior was generally cooperative.  There is a clear and well established class routine that the students seemed to follow, although a clear agenda for the lesson posted for the students' reference might further facilitate their understanding and expectations of the lesson.  The use of materials and presentation of information for tasks appeared to be efficient.  Teacher is effective in providing timing cues for the students.  Some additional reminders to the students to attend and listen to each others' responses might be useful in future lessons.
column57: Students are engaged in the lesson and tasks.  They are motivated by the tasks and are enthusiastic in their contributions/sharing out during the lesson.  The teacher is asking questions to check for understanding.  Questions posed are challenging and students are thinking about solving the posed physics problems using higher level thinking skills.  It was difficult to determine if LD students were able to contribute to the discussion.  More specific differentiation during the lesson and scaffolds for LD students are very important elements to include in future lessons.
column59: Teacher is able to reflect upon her teaching practice and provides practical and meaningful suggestions to improve her delivery/presentation of the lesson in the future.  Teacher is very welcoming of suggestions provided to her and is willing to incorporate new strategies into future lessons.

column49: This was a very effective and well planned lesson on how to use Rubrics to ensure high quality research outcomes in Global History studies. Teacher clearly planned and presented objectives and outcomes for the students. The key concepts of the lesson were clearly explained and activities that followed were appropriately aligned with the lesson content and key objectives. Teacher included  differentiated supports during group discussions and note taking to scaffold learning for the IEP students in the class.
column53: This is a very positive and cooperative learning environment for the students.  Class routines are well established, agenda is readily viewable on the board and students are clear regarding the high expectations teachers encourage from the students.  Pacing for this lesson was well done, including student cues and use of timer.  Instructional time was maximized as students efficiently transition to small groups.  Use of materials and turn and talk exercises were effective.
column57: Students are motivated and appropriately engaged in the lesson activities and the lesson discussions.  Teacher is providing students with higher level questions that serve to challenge their thinking, develop their skills and also to check for their understanding  Students are effectively assessed during group discussions as well as 1:1 in small groups. Students appear to be aware of the assessment learning criteria, and learned the meaningful use of rubrics in historical research.  Well planned graphic organizers were also incorporated into the lesson to further facilitate the students' understanding and effective research strategies.
column59: Teacher is very effective in her ability to reflect upon her teaching practice with the students.  She is able to provide productive and practical strategies to improve her work in the class with the students.  Teacher is able to cite examples of effective strategies used in the class, as well as those that might be improved for future lessons.

column49: Lesson plan used is gives much information.  It includes groupings, objectives connection to Standards and IEP goals.  It is written in specifics which make it easy for any staff (Para, Substitute)  to follow the plan.The strategies during the part of the lesson was for students to sit in a line  and watch him diring the read aloud.  He stopped several times during his reading to ask comprehension questions and to redirect behavior of student talking or walking around.  Students were able to answer questions such as "Who is telling this story? , What was the wold looking for as he went from house to house?  When the story was finished students were asked to verbally tell him what were some of the same concepts in this story as the classic story of the 3 Little Pigs.  Several times during his read aloud the students becale restless and needed to walk round however they were still listening to his reading and were able to answer correctly when questions were asked.
column53: There are several routines and systems in place however students get restless.  Students need to walk around but listen to his directions when asked to return to seat.  It is my suggestion that there needs to be more interactive activities during a read aloud.  If the text was placed on the smartboard, student could have an easier time following along.  There can be visuals used in the classroom to help students remember the class rules.  There can be a behavior chart on the board with the use of reminders of how they need to earn their stars, checks or points.
column57: The lesson plan did not state any specific assessment done during the lesson.  There was questioning during the reading but no data collection was evident.
column59: Noah has been able to grasp several of the skill needed to teach a 12:1:1 students.  He has established classroom routines and systems .  He also has been able to work with his para's to make his students more independent during independent work.  His behavioral routines are still in need of a more specific program that will motivate students to follow his rules.  When reminders are given the students react well and listen to his directions but students need reminding several times during his lesson.  Overal his teaching is improving with each observation I conduct.
